    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Citation cleanup</strong> is the corrective process of updating, removing, or merging inaccurate business listings and NAP data across directories, data aggregators, and review platforms — typically after a citation audit has revealed problems. Whitespark benchmarks show cleanup usually lifts local rankings <strong>2 to 5 positions within 30 to 90 days</strong>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical duration</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2–3 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Expected lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2–5 positions</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">First results</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Within 30 days</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Cleanup is the highest-ROI move in local SEO for any business that has ever relocated, changed phones, or rebranded. The audit tells you what's broken. The cleanup ships the fixes and pulls the rankings back.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is citation cleanup?</h2>
        <p>Citation cleanup is the write-action follow-up to a <a href="/glossary/citation-audit/">citation audit</a>. Where the audit produced a discrepancy list, cleanup executes against it — updating wrong addresses, correcting outdated phones, merging duplicate profiles, and removing stale entries.</p>
        <p>Typical cleanup work includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Update actions</strong> — correcting NAP fields on listings you own or can claim</li>
          <li><strong>Correction requests</strong> — submitting change requests to directories that don't allow direct edits</li>
          <li><strong>Merge / dedupe</strong> — consolidating multiple GBP or Yelp profiles into one</li>
          <li><strong>Removal</strong> — deleting listings for closed locations or ex-brands</li>
          <li><strong>Aggregator resubmission</strong> — pushing correct data through Data Axle, Neustar, Foursquare, and Factual so it propagates downstream</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why cleanup outperforms building</div>
          <p>Adding 50 clean citations on top of 30 wrong ones creates more conflict, not more trust. Fixing the 30 wrong ones first — even without adding any new citations — is often the single biggest ranking mover for local businesses.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why citation cleanup matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>Wrong citations don't just fail to help — they actively hurt. Four mechanisms:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ranking suppression.</strong> Google reads conflicting NAP data as reason to distrust your listing. Fixing conflicts lifts the confidence score.</li>
          <li><strong>Lost customers.</strong> Wrong phone numbers and outdated addresses route real prospects to nowhere. One retainer we ran surfaced a plumber whose old number was still on 40 directories two years after switching lines.</li>
          <li><strong>Fragmented signals.</strong> Duplicate listings split reviews and ranking authority between profiles that should be one entity.</li>
          <li><strong>Wasted budget.</strong> Every dollar spent on new citations while errors persist buys confusion instead of authority.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How citation cleanup actually works</h2>
        <p>Three-step workflow, repeated once per problem listing.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Step 1 — Prioritize by directory authority</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Tier 1:</span> Google Business Profile <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Yelp <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Bing Places <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Facebook <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Apple<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Tier 2:</span> Data Axle <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Neustar <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Foursquare <span class="uf-arrow">·</span> Factual<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Tier 3:</span> Industry directories<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Tier 4:</span> Long-tail generic directories<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Step 2 — Correction method per directory</span><br>
          Claim + edit directly <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> if the directory allows it<br>
          Submit correction form <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> if not claimable<br>
          Email support <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> for stubborn or scraper directories<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Step 3 — Handle duplicates</span><br>
          Merge in-directory <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> preserves reviews on one profile<br>
          Or delete secondary <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> when merge isn't available
        </div>

        <h3>Correction methods by directory type</h3>
        <p>Owned platforms (GBP, Bing, Yelp) allow direct edits. Aggregators require account-based submission but propagate downstream automatically. Legacy directories often need email requests with proof of the correct data.</p>

        <h3>Duplicate handling</h3>
        <p>Duplicates are the highest-impact fix. Merging two duplicate GBP profiles consolidates review count, star average, and photo library into one listing — often the difference between position 4 and position 1 in the local pack.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Cleanup approaches compared</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Cost</th><th>Timeline</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
