        <h2 id="examples">Real citation cleanup examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Two-year-old phone number change</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company changed its main phone number two years before the cleanup. The audit surfaced 40 directories still showing the old number. After corrections, call volume from online sources <strong>increased 25%</strong> within a month — customers who had been dialing dead lines were suddenly reaching the business.</p>

        <h3>2. Duplicate Google listings</h3>
        <p>A dental practice had three duplicate GBP listings with fragmented reviews — 80, 30, and 15 respectively. After consolidating into one primary profile, the unified listing carried <strong>125 reviews</strong> and moved up 4 positions in the local pack.</p>

        <h3>3. Relocated office data lingering</h3>
        <p>A law firm relocated 18 months prior. The cleanup surfaced 35 directories still showing the old address. Post-corrections, local pack rankings for the money keyword lifted 3 positions within 60 days.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Citation cleanup vs citation building — which first?</h2>
        <p>Cleanup first. Building second. Reversing the order buries clean citations under the noise of the broken ones.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Start with cleanup when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have any citations already (nearly everyone does)</li>
              <li>You've relocated, rebranded, or changed phone</li>
              <li>You suspect duplicate GBP or Yelp profiles</li>
              <li>Local rankings dropped without a Google update</li>
              <li>NAP appears inconsistent across the first 10 Google results for your brand name</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Go straight to building when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Brand-new business with zero online footprint</li>
              <li>Fresh GBP, no legacy directory presence</li>
              <li>Audit returns clean — no errors, no duplicates</li>
              <li>Multi-location expansion into new geography</li>
              <li>You genuinely have never been listed anywhere</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for citation cleanup</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Fix in tier order.</strong> GBP first, then Yelp / Bing / Apple, then the four aggregators, then everything else. Rankings respond most to the top tier.</li>
          <li><strong>Merge before you delete.</strong> Merging duplicates preserves reviews. Deleting loses them permanently.</li>
          <li><strong>Push through aggregators.</strong> A correction on Data Axle propagates to hundreds of downstream directories over 4–8 weeks — cheaper than fixing them one by one.</li>
          <li><strong>Track corrections in a sheet.</strong> Directory, correction date, verified date, notes. You need the paper trail for the ranking impact report.</li>
          <li><strong>Verify propagation at 6 weeks.</strong> Re-run the audit tool six weeks after aggregator submission to confirm downstream directories updated.</li>
          <li><strong>Establish a canonical NAP document.</strong> Locking canonical prevents the next round of drift when someone else creates new listings.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — cleaning citations without a canonical NAP</div>
          <p>If you fix 40 directories to slightly different versions of your NAP, you've done the work of a cleanup and gotten the outcome of a build-without-audit — new conflicts to detect and fix again in six months. Lock canonical first, cite the same string everywhere.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common citation cleanup mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Cleaning without an audit</strong> — you'll miss the listings you don't know exist</li>
          <li><strong>Deleting duplicate GBP profiles</strong> — you lose those reviews forever; merge instead</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring aggregators</strong> — corrections revert as the aggregators re-push old data</li>
          <li><strong>No canonical NAP</strong> — introduces new inconsistencies during the fix</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping verification</strong> — some directories accept the request but never publish it</li>
          <li><strong>One-time cleanup</strong> — drift returns; schedule the next audit in 6 months</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
